CSS Selectors

helps us choose where to apply our css.

We've seen that we can create css rules by simply specifying two things,
oen is the property we wanna change and after the color we get to specify the value
of the property

eg: color: blue
we are saying, we want to change the color to blue color


h1{ <----- this is called a CSS selector
    color : blue
}

what is a css selector?
it's the part that selects the html in order to apply whichever rules go into the
curly braces.

this style of selector is the simplest css selector
it's called the element selector.

Element Selector

when we select elements selector
like
p
a
h2
h1,
it means, apply to all the elements that have that particular tag.

Class Selector
eg.

.red-heading{
    color: red
}

this requires a special symbol which is dot, after the dot without the spaces
is class name eg red-heading, after the curly braces, we apply the css rules


what is a class ?
A class is something that we can add as an attribute to any HTML element
and this attribute is kinda like saying, let's group these particular elements in class
used to group elements to apply the same css rules to all the elements
in that class.

how to we set a class

<h1 class="red-text">Red</h1>

and when we write css and target the class
then

.red-text{ <- have to be spelled same as the class name
    color:red;
}

then it selects the only element that has the class name same as that we
specified in the class selector
and applies the css style

this can be really useful on multi-page websites with lots of different elements,
and you don't just want to select a particular type of HTML element.



# ID selector
is has it's own special symbol (#)

#main{
    color:red
}
this selects all the element with a particular id attribute


eg
<h2 id="main">Red</h2>
works similarly to class selector

difference between class vs id
- class selector can be applied to many element
- id can be applied on one element in a single html file


# Attribute Selector
Another way that you can select parts of your html is using the attribute selector
so we know that we can create a html tag and add as many attributes we like

# we can select these elements that have particular attributes or particular attributes values
by using this notation

first part is html element, then set of square brackets and the attribute we wanna select
this says, select all the paragraphs with attribute draggable and apply the css to it

p[draggable]{
    color: red
}


eg
<p draggable="true">Drag me</p>
<p>Don't drag me</p>
<p>Don't drag me</p>

if we give the css style, it will find the unique paragraph with that attribute
and apply the css to it.

we can also select the value of the attribute we want our css to attach to
<p draggable="true">Drag me</p>
<p draggable="false">Don't drag me</p>
<p draggable="false">Don't drag me</p>


# it will select all the para elements with draggable as false
p[draggable="false"]{
    color: red
}


# Universal Selector

*{
    color: red
}
it's just an asterix and after the asterix you have your css rule,
it means select all. it will apply the style to everything where the style sheet is active.
